And the Italian saith in his Proverbe; God keepe mee from the hurt of my friends, for I know well how to keepe me from mine enemies. From thence bound East-ward, I vi∣sited Naples, the commendations of which, I revolve in this verse;
Inclyta Parthenope gignit Comites{que} Duces{que}
Most noble Naples, breeds but Dukes and Earles,
And gallant Knights, and Ladies load with Pearles.

Twelve dayes was I between Rhodes and Limisso in Cy∣prus;
where arrived, I received more gracious demonstra∣tions
from the Islanders,The descrip∣tion of Cyprus then I could hope for, or wish,
being far beyond my merit or expectation; onely conten∣ting
my curiosity with a quiet minde, I red ounded thanks
for my imbraced courtesies.

The rest of the surnames of the Italian Dukes are
these, viz. that of Parma is Fernese, signifying Partridges;
that of Modena is Astie, that of Florence de Medicis;
that of Vrbine, Francesco Maria, and the last Duke of Man∣tua,
Gonsaga; the Dutchy of Ferrara, being dissolved, is
converted to the Popes patrimony.
